ops.insert: International trade will almost always benefit both countries, so why do countries try to protect their own firms from exposure to the world market?

textDelta: if International trade will almost always benefit both countries, so why do countries try to protect their own firms from exposure to the world market? The answer to this question is that it is not always clear whether a country will benefit from opening up to trade. The benefits of trade come from specialization and trade in the production of goods. This means that a country can benefit from trade if it specializes in the production of goods in which it has a comparative advantage. But what if a country is not very good at producing anything?
